Industrial applications have high requirements on the stability and cyclability of photocatalysts. Therefore, the stability of composite photocatalysts was investigated by LP-2 cyclic repeated experiments. At the end of each cycle, the recovery of the photocatalyst is carried out by washing, centrifugation and drying, and then it is continued to be used in the next cycle. Fig. 12
                        (a) shows that after four cycles of experiments, the adsorption rate of Cr (VI) remains at about 58%, and the removal rate remains above 90%. The chemical stability of LP-2 was reflected by the XRD spectra before and after the reaction (Fig. 12(b)). Although the strength of XRD diffraction peak decreased due to the “respiration effect” of the composite material, the main diffraction peak still existed. It shows that the structure of LP-2 is not damaged after four cycles, and it is still useable. The problem of ion leaching often exists in MOFs composites during photocatalytic degradation. In order to further verify the stability of our material, ion leaching experiments were performed in the process of LP-2 photocatalytic degradation of MB. During the long-term photocatalytic degradation of MB, the content of iron ion in the solution changed from 1.106 mg/L to 4.4452 mg/L. Partial leaching of iron ions may be one of the reasons for the reduction of catalytic efficiency, but the leaching content of iron ions is still much lower than that of the photocatalytic system. Finally, Fig. 12(c) and (d) show the SEM images of LP-2 before and after the cycle, respectively, indicating that the lamellar structure of g-C3N4 was not destroyed after the photocatalytic reaction, and MOF was still attached to the lamellar structure. In general, compared with other MOFs and g-C3N4 based photocatalysts, the composites in this experiment have good performance for photo-reduction of Cr(VI) and photodegradation of dyes. (Table 1
                        ), especially LP-2 has excellent reaction efficiency in both aspects.
